<A HREF="http://malignant.cjb.net">
<IMG SRC="http://freepages.ugo.com/woohoo/files/MALIGNANT.jpg"></A></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=FAEBD7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub73.ezboard.com/ugovindasz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Govinda SZ</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>poon</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(8/22/01 10:52:43 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: My comment to Verant re Spell Damage Nerf &amp; PvP Resi</span><hr size=1> &quot;If spell damage was nerfed because it was designed for PvE, why aren't Resists nerfed in accord with that same theory? It it common for high level players (40-60) on PvP servers to have Resists in the 150-200 range&quot;<br>
<br>
The reason spell damage was nerfed in PvP had nothing to do with resists, it had to do with HPs. Spells were balanced for use against NPCs, who have far more hitpoints than a PC of the same level.  Spell damage was reduced in PvP because PvP targets have a much fewer hp per level than NPCs. Nothing in the expansions has changed this significantly, the gap between hp totals of NPC and PC has actually grown wider. NPCs in the expansions have way more hps than mobs of comparable level pre-expansion, while player hp totals have not seen a comparable increase.<br>
<br>
Yes, a well equipped player will have higher resists than many NPCs of the same level. To compensate for this, resist reducing spells were improved by 50% when used in PvP. Not every class can cast these spells, but you can always group with someone who can.  Remember that pvp like pve is balanced for group combat not solo. In PvE at high levels wizards must use lures and are dependent on resist debuffing classes to be effective, why should this be different in PvP?<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;At high level pvp, as a wizard with 2.5 years of pvp experience, there is very little I cast besides Lures and Shock of Lightning.&quot;<br>
<br>
So most of your spells are not effective unless the target is resist debuffed, every class has this problem at higher levels.  Not every class gets resist debuffs, and those that do not are increasingly dependent on those that do as they level up.  You knew that wizards didn't have resist debuffs from the beginning, just like every cleric and hybrid knows that, the difference is your class has spells specifically designed to alleviate this problem (lures) where they do not.  Cleric and hybrid spells are TOTALLY ineffective at higher level without resist debuffs from a groupmate.<br>
<br>
If you think wizards should get some sort of resistance debuff spell, thats a valid point which I would probably support.  If you want to rebalance the way spell damage and resists work for everyone because you'd rather solo than group with a mage/ench/shaman who can reduce resists for you, I would not agree with that.<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;Are my Roots supposed to be worthless? <br>
Are my snares not supposed to ever land? <br>
Are my Clash spells supposed to be a waste?&quot;<br>
<br>
Any spell that can stop or slow the movement of a target SHOULD be relatively easy to resist. If they weren't this would tip the balance heavily against melee classes who have no way of causing damage when they can't keep up with their target.  Again, when a target has been resist debuffed these spells are much more effective, and again if you choose to solo rather than group you will find these spells much less effective.<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;resists are completely out of control&quot; <br>
many classes can reduce resists, if yours can't then group with one that can<br>
<br>
&quot;wizards are the most DD dependant and least able to debuff&quot; <br>
see above<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;Pet HP wasnt nerfed. <br>
Melee AC/HP/ATK/DEF wasnt nerfed. <br>
Heal Spells were not nerfed.&quot;<br>
<br>
Melee damage is a valid issue, which I'll deal with in a moment, the others have little to do with reduced spell damage and the reason behind it.  It just sounds like you're saying &quot;you nerfed me so you must nerf everyone else&quot;. I know I sound like a broken record, but this argument must be kept in the context of the issue being addressed by the damage nerf, that issue is: NPCS HAVE MORE HP THAN PCS.<br>
<br>
Spell damage is balanced vs NPC HP totals not vs PCs.<br>
Heals are already balanced for PC HP totals.<br>
Reducing PC and pet HP totals would aggravate the problem rather than solve it.<br>
<br>
As for melee damage, on the surface it seems like a fair argument that if spell damage is reduced against players, melee damage should be reduced by a similar proportion.  In my opinion, what makes this unnecessary are additional factors which make PvP combat more difficult for melee classes yet do not affect spellcasters.  In melee combat vs a NPC your target is nice enough to stand directly in front of you so you can hit it.  Landing melee attacks on a player target requires the additional effort of constantly chasing to keep them in melee range long enough to land a few hits, add to that graphics glitches (dissapearing on hillsides for example) that make this even more difficult than it should be.  For a spellcaster, PvP combat is essentially the same tactically as PvE combat, easier in fact since your opponent is not on auto-follow and you are not restricted by line of sight.  The fact that a melee must chase the target between melee attacks, jousting instead of standing still with auto-attack turned on, is a de facto melee damage nerf at least as great as the 1/3 reduction on spell damage.  The time spent chasing a PC would be used making additional attacks against an NPCs, leading to a higher damage output.<br>
<br>
Yes, Kunark and Velious resist items have increased resists making things harder for casters. They have also dramatically increased AC making things more difficult for melees.<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;if you are not going to remove the spell damage cap, then please at least be decent enough to similarly nerf the mana cost of the spell&quot;<br>
<br>
This defeats the entire purpose of the spell damage nerf.  Whats the point of reducing damage per spell against weaker targets (PCs) if the caster can inflict the same total damage per bar of mana?<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;[staff of temperate flux] currently reduces FIRE and COLD by SIX&quot;<br>
<br>
isn't it 9 now with the 50% resist debuff bonus? =)<br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;Shouldnt the most mana-dependent, DD dependent caster be able to debuff?&quot;<br>
<br>
Maybe. But adding a debuff to wizards and overhauling the entire pvp balance just to suit you as a solo wizard is a bit different.<br>
<br>
